Notable employees[edit]

George Becker, former vice president of the AFL-CIO, and president of the United Steelworkers; worked at a Dow's aluminum rolling mill in Madison, Illinois, where he was a shop steward.[129]
Buddy Burris, professional football player with the Green Bay Packers; worked for Dow following his football career.[130]
Norman F. Carnahan, chemical engineer; worked at Dow's Plaquemines Parish, Louisiana division from 1965 to 1968.[131]
Sven Trygve Falck, Norwegian engineer, businessperson and politician; Dow engineer in Texas from 1967 to 1970.[132]
Larry Garner, Louisiana blues musician; worked at Dow's Baton Rouge, Louisiana facility.[133]
Bettye Washington Greene, first African-American female chemist employed at Dow; began working in 1965 at the E.C. Britton Lab.[134]
Alexandre Hohagen, vice president for Latin America and US Hispanics at Facebook; former public relations manager for Dow Chemical Brazil.[135]
Zdravko Ježić, Olympic silver medalist; worked for Dow in Texas on the development of urethane and oxide polymers.[136]
Claude-André Lachance, youngest person elected to the Canadian House of Commons (prior to 2011); director of public affairs for Dow Canada.[137]
Ray McIntire, inventor of styrofoam; began working for Dow in 1940 and became a research director.[138]
Fred McLafferty, chemist who pioneered the technique of gas chromatography-mass spectrometry; began working at Dow's organic chemistry research laboratory in Midland, Michigan in the 1950s.[139]
John Moolenaar, member of the Michigan Senate and Michigan House of Representatives; worked as a chemist for Dow.[140]
George Andrew Olah, recipient of 1994 Nobel Prize in Chemistry; employed at Dow's Sarnia, Canada plant in the late 1950s.[141]
Forrest Parry, inventor of the magnetic stripe card; worked for Dow in the 1950s.[142]
Roy A. Periana, American organometallic chemist; worked for Dow at Midland, Michigan.[143]
Abu Ammaar Yasir Qadhi, conservative American Islamic cleric; worked for Dow after obtaining a chemical engineering degree from the University of Houston.[144]
Abraham Quintanilla, Jr., singer-songwriter; former shipping clerk at Dow's Freeport, Texas facility.[145]
Sheldon Roberts, semiconductor pioneer who helped found Silicon Valley; former technical researcher at Dow.[146]
Alexander Shulgin, chemist and pharmacologist credited with introducing the drug MDMA ("ecstasy") to psychologists in the late 1970s; worked for Dow in the 1960s, where he invented Zectran, the first biodegradable insecticide.[147]
Mary P. Sinclair, environmental activist; former technical researcher at Dow.[148]
Huimin Zhao, Centennial Endowed Chair of Chemical and Bio-Molecular Engineering at the University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign; project leader at Dow's Industrial Biotechnology Laboratory.[149]

